description: The Law of Mass Action, first expressed by Waage and Guldberg in 1864 (Waage, P.; Guldberg, C. M. Forhandlinger: Videnskabs-Selskabet i Christiana 1864, 35) states that the speed of a chemical reaction is proportional to the quantity of the reacting substances. More formally, the change of a product quantity is proportional to the product of reactant activities. In the case of a reaction occurring in a gas phase, the activities are equal to the partial pressures. In the case of a well-stirred aqueous medium, the activities are equal to the concentrations. In the case of discrete kinetic description, the quantity are expressed in number of molecules and the relevant volume are implicitely embedded in the kinetic constant.
terms.label: mass action rate law

description: First general rate equation for reactions involving enzymes, it was presented in "Victor Henri. Lois Générales de l'Action des Diastases. Paris, Hermann, 1903.". The reaction is assumed to be made of a reversible of the binding of the substrate to the enzyme, followed by the breakdown of the complex generating the product. Ten years after Henri, Michaelis and Menten presented a variant of his equation, based on the hypothesis that the dissociation rate of the substrate was much larger than the rate of the product generation. Leonor Michaelis, Maud Menten (1913). Die Kinetik der Invertinwirkung, Biochem. Z. 49:333-369.

Although of the same form than the Henri-Michaelis-Menten equation, it is semantically different since K now represents the ratio between the production rate and the association rate of the enzyme and the substrate.

description: The Briggs-Haldane rate law is a general rate equation that does not require the restriction of equilibrium of Henri-Michaelis-Menten or irreversible reactions of Van Slyke, but instead make the hypothesis that the complex enzyme-substrate is in quasi-steady-state. Although of the same form than the Henri-Michaelis-Menten equation, it is semantically different since Km now represents a pseudo-equilibrium constant, and is equal to the ratio between the rate of consumption of the complex (sum of dissociation of substrate and generation of product) and the association rate of the enzyme and the substrate.

Those influences can be well-defined physical perturbations, such as a light pulse, or a change in temperature but also more complex of not well defined phenomena, for instance a biological process, an experimental setup, or a mutation.
terms.label: biological effect of a perturbation

description: A biochemical network can generate phenotypes or affects biological processes. Such processes can take place at different levels and are independent of the biochemical network itself.
terms.label: phenotype

description: A chemical moiety that exists under different forms but is not created nor destroyed in a biochemical system. In any given system such a conserved moiety is characterized by a finite number of particles that exist in the system and is invariant.
terms.label: mass conservation law

description: The enumeration of co-localised, identical biochemical entities of a specific state, which constitute a pool. The form of enumeration may be purely numerical, or may be given in relation to another dimension such as length or volume.
terms.label: quantity of an entity pool

description: A numerical measure of the quantity, or of some property, of the entities that constitute the entity pool.
terms.label: amount of an entity pool

description: If all forms of a moiety exist in a single compartment and the size of that compartment is fixed then the Mass Conservation is also a Concentration Conservation.
terms.label: concentration conservation law

description: Synonym: Kx
terms.label: activation constant

description: Number of monomers composing a multimeric entity.
terms.label: multimer cardinality

description: Numerical parameter that quantifies the forward velocity of a chemical reaction where reactants have non-integral orders. This parameter encompasses all the contributions to the velocity except the quantity of the reactants.It is to be used in a reaction modelled using a continuous framework.
terms.label: forward non-integral order rate constant, continuous case

description: Numerical parameter that quantifies the forward velocity of a chemical reaction where reactants have non-integral orders. This parameter encompasses all the contributions to the velocity except the quantity of the reactants. It is to be used in a reaction modelled using a discrete framework.
terms.label: forward non-integral order rate constant, discrete case

description: Numerical parameter that quantifies the reverse velocity of a chemical reaction where products have non-integral orders. This parameter encompasses all the contributions to the velocity except the quantity of the products. It is to be used in a reaction modelled using a discrete framework.
terms.label: reverse non-integral order rate constant, discrete case

description: Numerical parameter that quantifies the reverse velocity of a chemical reaction where products have non-integral orders. This parameter encompasses all the contributions to the velocity except the quantity of the products. It is to be used in a reaction modelled using a continuous framework.
terms.label: reverse non-integral order rate constant, continuous case

description: Region of a gene that is involved in the modulation of the expression of the gene.
terms.label: gene regulatory region

description: Michaelis constant derived or experimentally measured under non-equilibrium conditions.
terms.label: Michaelis constant in non-equilibrium situation

description: Michaelis constant derived using a steady-state assumption for enzyme-substrate and enzyme-product intermediates. For example see Briggs-Haldane equation (SBO:0000031).
terms.label: Michaelis constant in quasi-steady state situation

description: Michaelis constant derived assuming enzyme-substrate and enzyme-product intermediates are formed in consecutive irreversible reactions. The constant K is the ratio of the forward rate constants. For example see Van Slyke-Cullen equation (SBO:0000030).
terms.label: Michaelis constant in irreversible situation

description: Michaelis constant as determined in a reaction where the formation of the enzyme-substrate complex occurs at a much faster rate than subsequent steps, and so are assumed to be in a quasi-equilibrium situation. K is equivalent to an equilibrium constant. For example see Henri-Michaelis-Menten equation (SBO:0000029).
terms.label: Michaelis constant in fast equilibrium situation

description: connectedness between entities and/or interactions representing their relatedness or influence.
terms.label: relationship

description: A sequential series of actions, motions, or occurrences, such as chemical reactions, that affect one or more entities in a phenomenologically characteristic manner.
terms.label: process

description: Decomposition of a compound by reaction with water, where the hydroxyl and H groups are incorporated into different products
terms.label: hydrolysis

description: A reaction in which the principal reactant and principal product are isomers of each other
terms.label: isomerisation

description: Inhibition of a unireactant enzyme by competing substrates (Sa) that bind to the free enzyme on the same binding site. The enzyme does not catalyse the reactions in both directions.
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for inhibition of irreversible unireactant enzymes by competing substrates

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for competitive inhibition of irreversible unireactant enzymes by exclusive inhibitors

description: Inhibition of a unireactant enzyme by two inhibitors that can bind once to the free enzyme and preclude the binding of the substrate. Binding of one inhibitor may affect binding of the other, or not. The enzymes do not catalyse the reactions in both directions.
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for simple competitive inhibition of irreversible unireactant enzymes by two non-exclusive inhibitors

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for modulated unireactant enzymes

description: number used as a multiplicative or exponential factor for quantities, expressions or functions
terms.label: biochemical coefficient

description: A multiplicative factor for quantities, expressions or functions
terms.label: biochemical proportionality coefficient

description: number used as an exponential factor for quantities, expressions or functions
terms.label: biochemical exponential coefficient

description: The coefficient used to quantify the effect on inhibition constants of multiple inhibitors binding non-exclusively to the enzyme.
terms.label: biochemical cooperative inhibition coefficient

description: Coefficient that quantifies the effect on inhibition constants of either binding of multiple substrates or inhibitors.
terms.label: biochemical inhibitory proportionality coefficient

description: The coefficient that describes the proportional change of Ks or Ki when inhibitor or substrate is bound, respectively, to the enzyme.
terms.label: biochemical cooperative inhibitor substrate coefficient

description: Inhibition of a unireactant enzyme by a competing substrate (Sa) that binds to the free enzyme on the same binding site. The enzyme does not catalyse the reactions in both directions.
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for inhibition of irreversible unireactant enzymes by single competing substrate

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for inhibition of irreversible unireactant enzymes by competing substrates

description: Inhibition of a unireactant enzyme by a competing product (P) that binds to the free enzyme on the same binding site. The enzyme does not catalyse the reactions in both directions.
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for competitive inhibition of irreversible unireactant enzyme by product

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for competitive inhibition of irreversible unireactant enzymes by exclusive inhibitors

description: Inhibition of a unireactant enzyme by a competing substrate (Sa) that binds to the free enzyme on the same binding site, and competitive inhibition by a product (P) and an alternative product (Pa). The enzyme does not catalyse the reactions in both directions.
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for inhibition of irreversible unireactant enzymes by single competing substrate with product inhibition

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for inhibition of irreversible unireactant enzymes by competing substrates

description: A parameter value taken by a switch, which has a discrete set of values which can be alternated or switched between.
terms.label: switch value

description: Synonym: binary switch
terms.label: boolean switch

description: A mathematical expression that describes a steady state situation
terms.label: steady state expression

description: Term to signify those material or conceptual entities that are identical in some respect within a frame of reference
terms.label: equivalence

description: Generation of a material or conceptual entity.
terms.label: production

description: Decrease in amount of a material or conceptual entity.
terms.label: consumption

description: An aggregation of interactions and entities into a single process.
terms.label: encapsulating process

description: An equivocal or conjectural process, whose existence is assumed but not proven.
terms.label: uncertain process

description: One or more processes that are not represented in certain representations or interpretations of a model.
terms.label: omitted process

description: Relationship between entities (material or conceptual) and logical operators, or between logical operators themselves.
terms.label: logical relationship

description: A process in which a carboxyl group (COOH) is removed from a molecule as carbon dioxide.
terms.label: decarboxylation

description: Removal of a carbonyl group (-C-O-) from a molecule, usually as carbon monoxide
terms.label: decarbonylation

description: Removal of an amine group from a molecule, often under the addition of water
terms.label: deamination

description: Covalent reaction that results in the transfer of a chemical group from one molecule to another.
terms.label: transfer of a chemical group

description: The transfer of an amino group between two molecules. Commonly in biology this is restricted to reactions between an amino acid and an alpha-keto carbonic acid, whereby the reacting amino acid is converted into an alpha-keto acid, and the alpha-keto acid reactant into an amino acid.
terms.label: transamination

description: Functional entity associated with or derived from a unit of inheritance.
terms.label: unit of genetic information

description: A material entity that is responsible for a perturbing effect
terms.label: perturbing agent

description: An entity that can be measured quantitatively
terms.label: observable

description: Control that precludes the execution of a process.
terms.label: absolute inhibition

description: Effect of a biological entity on biological structures or processes.
terms.label: biological activity

description: Entity that results from the interaction between other entities.
terms.label: interaction outcome

description: A compartment whose existence is inferred due to the presence of known material entities which must be bounded, allowing the creation of material entity pools.
terms.label: implicit compartment

description: Control that always triggers the controlled process.
terms.label: absolute stimulation

description: The potential action that a biological entity has on other entities. Example are enzymatic activity, binding activity etc.
terms.label: biological activity

description: The connectedness between entities as related by their position
terms.label: positional relationship

description: Positional relationship between entities on the same strand (e.g. in DNA), or on the same side.
terms.label: cis

description: Positional relationship between entities on different sides, or strands
terms.label: trans

description: One of the two values possible from a boolean switch, which equates to '1', 'on' or 'input'.
terms.label: true

description: One of the two values possible from a boolean switch, which equates to '0', 'off' or 'no input'.
terms.label: false

description: Non-covalent association between several independant complexes
terms.label: multimer of complexes

description: Non-covalent association between portions of macromolecules that carry genetic information
terms.label: multimer of informational molecule segment

description: Non-covalent association between several macromolecules
terms.label: multimer of macromolecules

description: Non-covalent association between several simple chemicals
terms.label: multimer of simple chemicals

description: Inhibitory constant for the binding of a given ligand with an isomeric form of an enzyme.
terms.label: isoinhibition constant

description: In reversible reactions this is the concentration of product that is required to achieve half activation or inhibition in Hill-type kinetics, in the absence of the substrate.
terms.label: pseudo-dissociation constant for product

description: In reversible reactions this is the concentration of substrate that is required to achieve half activation or inhibition in Hill-type kinetics, in the absence of the product.
terms.label: pseudo-dissociation constant for substrate

description: Reversible Hill-type kinetics represents the situation where a single substrate and product bind cooperatively and reversibly to the enzyme. Co-operativity is seen if the Hill coefficient (h) is greater than 1, indicating that the binding of one substrate (or product) molecule facilitates the binding of the next. The opposite effect is evident with a coefficient less than 1.
terms.label: reversible Hill-type enzymatic rate law

description: Reversible Hill-type kinetics in the presence of at least one modifier whose binding is affected by the presence of the substrate or product.
terms.label: modulated reversible Hill-type rate law

description: The modifier can be either an activator or inhibitor depending on the value of alpha (activator for values larger than 1, inhibitor for values smaller than 1; no effect if exactly 1). This reflects the effect of the presence of substrate and product on the binding of the modifier. The equation, derived by Hofmeyr and Cornish-Bowden (Comput. Appl. Biosci. 13, 377 - 385 (1997)
terms.label: modulated reversible Hill-type rate law with one modifier

description:
The modifiers can be either activators or inhibitors depending on the values of and alpha (activators for values larger than 1, inhibitors for values smaller than 1; no effect if exactly 1). The assumption is that the binding of one modifier affects the binding of the second. Modifiers are assumed to bind at different sites.  The synergetic effects of the two modifiers depend on the parameter alpha (if unity then they are independent; if zero they compete for the same binding site). and reflect the effect of the presence of substrate and product on the binding of modifier A or modifier B. alphaA and  alphaB  factors account for the effect of substrate and product binding on the binding of modifier A and modifier B respectively. alphaAB accounts for the interaction of the modifiers on each others binding.
  (if < 1 Ma is inhibitor, if > 1 activator)
alpha_2 	: factor accounting for the effect of S and P on the binding of Mb
  (if < 1 Mb is inhibitor, if > 1 activator)
alpha_3 	: factor accounting for interaction of Ma to Mb binding to the enzyme (and v. v.).
terms.label: modulated reversible Hill-type rate law with two modifiers

description: Kinetics of enzyme-catalysed reactions with 2 or more substrates or products
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for multireactant enzymes

description: Kinetics of enzymes that react with one substance, and whose activity may be positively or negatively modulated.
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for modulated unireactant enzymes

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for unireactant enzymes

description: Reversible equivalent of Hill kinetics, where substrate and product bind co-operatively to the enzyme. A Hill coefficient (h) of greater than 1 indicates positive co-operativity between substrate and product, while h values below 1 indicate negative co-operativity.
terms.label: unmodulated reversible Hill-type rate law

description: Enzymatic rate law for an irreversible reaction involving two substrates and one product.
terms.label: irreversible Michaelis Menten rate law for two substrates

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for multireactant enzymes

description: Enzymatic rate law for a reaction involving two substrates and two products. The products P and then Q are released strictly in order, while the substrates are bound strictly in the order A and then B.
terms.label: Ordered Bi-Bi mechanism rate law

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for multireactant enzymes

description: Enzymatic rate for a reaction involving two substrates and one product. The substrates A and then B are bound strictly in order.
terms.label: Ordered Bi-Uni mechanism rate law

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for multireactant enzymes

description: Enzymatic rate law for a reaction with one substrate and two products. The products P and then Q are released in the strict order P and then Q.
terms.label: Ordered Uni-Bi mechanism rate law

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for multireactant enzymes

description: Enzymatic rate law for a reaction involving two substrates and two products. The first product (P) is released after the first substrate (A) has been bound. The second product (Q) is released after the second substrate (B) has been bound.
terms.label: Ping Pong Bi-Bi mechanism rate law

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for multireactant enzymes

description: Enzyme catalysed reaction involving one substrate and one product. Unlike the reversible uni-uni mechanism (SBO:0000326), the mechanism assumes an enzyme intermediate. Therefore, the free enzyme generated after the release of product from enzyme-product complex is not the same form as that which bind the substrate to form enzyme-substrate complex. Some permeases are thought to follow this mechanism, such that isomerization in the membrane may be accomplished through re-orientation in the membrane.
terms.label: reversible Iso Uni-Uni

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for non-modulated unireactant enzymes

description: Synonym: Uni-Uni Reversible Simple Michaelis-Menten
terms.label: reversible Uni-Uni

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for non-modulated unireactant enzymes

description: Synonym: Uni-Uni
terms.label: Uni-Uni Reversible using Haldane relationship

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for non-modulated unireactant enzymes

description: Enzymatic rate law which follows from the allosteric concerted model (symmetry model or MWC model).This states that enzyme subunits can assume one of two conformational states (relaxed or tense), and that the state of one subunit is shared or enforced on the others. The binding of a ligand to a site other than that bound by the substrate (active site) can shift the conformation from one state to the other. L represents the equilibrium constant between active and inactive states of the enzyme, and n represents the number of binding sites for the substrate and inhibitor.
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for irreversible allosteric inhibition

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for modulated unireactant enzymes

description: Reversible inhibition of a unireactant enzyme by inhibitors that can bind to the enzyme-substrate complex and to the free enzyme with the same equilibrium constant. The inhibitor is noncompetitive with the substrate.
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for mixed-type inhibition of reversible enzymes by mutually exclusive inhibitors

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for mixed-type inhibition of irreversible enzymes by mutually exclusive inhibitors

description: Reversible inhibition of a unireactant enzyme by one inhibitor that can bind to the enzyme-substrate complex and to the free enzyme with the same equilibrium constant. The inhibitor is noncompetitive with the substrate.
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for simple reversible non-competitive inhibition of unireactant enzymes

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for simple mixed-type inhibition of irreversible unireactant enzymes

description: Synonym: specific activation
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for reversible essential activation

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for modulated unireactant enzymes

description: Enzymatic rate law where the activator enhances the rate of reaction through specific and catalytic effects, which increase the apparent limiting rate and decrease apparent Michaelis constant. The activator can bind reversibly both the free enzyme and enzyme-substrate complex, while the substrate can bind only to enzyme-activator complex. Catalytic activity is seen only when enzyme, substrate and activator are complexed.
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for reversible mixed activation

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for reversible essential activation

description: This enzymatic rate law is available only for irreversible reactions, with one substrate and one product. There is a second binding site for the enzyme which, when occupied, activates the enzyme. Substrate binding at either site can occur at random.
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for irreversible substrate activation

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for reversible mixed activation

description: Enzymatic rate law where the activator enhances the rate of reaction through specific and catalytic effects, which increase the apparent limiting rate and decrease apparent Michaelis constant. The activator can bind irreversibly both free enzyme and enzyme-substrate complex, while the substrate can bind only to enzyme-activator complex. Catalytic activity is seen only when enzyme, substrate and activator are complexed.
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for irrreversible mixed activation

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for reversible mixed activation

description: Enzymatic rate law where an activator enhances the rate of reaction by increasing the apparent limiting rate; The reversible binding of the activator to the enzyme-substrate complex is required for enzyme catalytic activity (to generate the product).
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for reversible catalytic activation with one activator

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for reversible mixed activation

description: Enzymatic rate law for one substrate, one product and one modifier which acts as an activator. The activator enhances the rate of reaction by decreasing the apparent Michaelis constant. The activator reversibly binds to the enzyme before the enzyme can bind the substrate.
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for reversible specific activation

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for reversible mixed activation

description: Enzymatic rate law where an activator enhances the rate of reaction by increasing the apparent limiting rate; The activator binding to the enzyme-substrate complex (irreversibly) is required for enzyme catalytic activity (to generate the product).
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for irreversible catalytic activation with one activator

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for reversible catalytic activation with one activator

description: Enzymatic rate law for one substrate, one product and one modifier which acts as an activator. The activator enhances the rate of reaction by decreasing the apparent Michaelis constant. The activator must bind to the enzyme before the enzyme can bind the substrate.
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for irreversible specific activation

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for reversible specific activation

description: This enzymatic rate law involves one substrate, one product and one or more modifiers. The modifiers act as competitive inhibitors of the substrate at the enzyme binding site; The modifiers (inhibitors) reversibly bound to the enzyme block access to the substrate. The inhibitors have the effect of increasing the apparent Km, and bind exclusively to the enzymes.
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for reversible reactions with competitive inhibition

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for modulated unireactant enzymes

description: This enzymatic rate law involves one substrate, one product and one modifier. The modifier acts as a competitive inhibitor with the substrate at the enzyme binding site; The modifier (inhibitor) reversibly bound to the enzyme blocks access to the substrate. The inhibitor has the effect of increasing the apparent Km.
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for reversible competitive inhibition by one inhibitor

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for reversible reactions with competitive inhibition

description: Enzymatic rate law where the reversible binding of one ligand decreases the affinity for substrate at other active sites. The ligand does not bind the same site as the substrate on the enzyme. This is an empirical equation, where n represents the Hill coefficient.
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for reversible empirical allosteric inhibition by one inhibitor

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for reversible reactions with competitive inhibition

description: Enzymatic rate law where the substrate for an enzyme also acts as a reversible  inhibitor. This may entail a second (non-active) binding site for the enzyme. The inhibition constant is then the dissociation constant for the substrate from this second site.
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for reversible substrate inhibition

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for modulated unireactant enzymes

description: Enzymatic rate law where the substrate for an enzyme also acts as an irreversible inhibitor. This may entail a second (non-active) binding site for the enzyme. The inhibition constant is then the dissociation constant for the substrate from this second site.
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for irreversible substrate inhibition

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for reversible substrate inhibition

description:
Enzymatic rate law where the modifier can act as an activator or inhibitor, depending upon the values of the kinetic constants. The modifier can bind reversibly to all forms of the enzyme and all enzyme-substrate complexes are reactive. 
'a' represents the ratio of dissociation constant of the elementary step Enzyme-Substrate complex + Modifier = Enzyme-Substrate-Modifier complex over that of Enzyme + Modifier = Enzyme-Modifier complex.
'b' represents ratio of the rate constant of elementary step Enzyme-Substrate-Modifier complex -> Enzyme-Modifier complex + Product over that of Enzyme-Substrate complex -> Enzyme + Product.
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for reversible unireactant enzyme with a single hyperbolic modulator

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for modulated unireactant enzymes

description:
Enzymatic rate law where the modifier can act as an activator or inhibitor, depending upon the values of the kinetic constants. The modifier can bind irreversibly to all forms of the enzyme and all enzyme-substrate complexes are reactive. 
'a' represents the ratio of dissociation constant of the elementary step Enzyme-Substrate complex + Modifier = Enzyme-Substrate-Modifier complex) over that of Enzyme + Modifier = Enzyme-Modifier complex.
'b' represents ratio of the rate constant of elementary step Enzyme-Substrate-Modifier complex -> Enzyme-Modifier complex + Product over that of Enzyme-Substrate complex -> Enzyme + Product.
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for irreversible unireactant enzyme with a single hyperbolic modulator

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for reversible unireactant enzyme with a single hyperbolic modulator

description: Reversible inhibition of a unireactant enzyme by one inhibitor, which binds to the enzyme-substrate complex. The inhibitor is uncompetitive with the substrate.
terms.label: enzymatic rate law for simple uncompetitive inhibition of reversible unireactant enzymes

parents.label: enzymatic rate law for modulated unireactant enzymes

description: Synonym: activator
terms.label: stimulator

description: A substance that accelerates the velocity of a chemical reaction without itself being consumed or transformed, by lowering the free energy of the transition state. The substance acting as a catalyst is an enzyme.
terms.label: enzymatic catalyst

description: Synonym: necessary stimulator
terms.label: essential activator

description: An activator which is not necessary for an enzymatic reaction, but whose presence will further increase enzymatic activity.
terms.label: non-essential activator

description: Synonym: standard chemical potential
terms.label: standard biochemical potential

description: Assignment of a state or a value to a state variable, characteristic or property, of a biological entity.
terms.label: state variable assignment

description: The measurable dimensions of an object which are minimally required to define the space that an object occupies.
terms.label: spatial measure

description: The length of an object is the longest measurable distance between its extremities.
terms.label: length

description: The area of an object is a quantity expressing its two-dimensional size, usually part or all of its surface.
terms.label: area

description: A quantity representing the three-dimensional space occupied by all or part of an object.
terms.label: volume

description: Synonym: inclusion
terms.label: containment

description: For a given substance, A, its mass fraction (x A) is defined as the ratio of its mass (m A) to the total mass (m total) in which it is present, where the sum of all mass fractions is equal to 1. This provides a means to express concentration in a dimensionless size.
terms.label: mass fraction

description: Molality denotes the number of moles of solute per kilogram of solvent (not solution). The term molal solution is used as a shorthand for a "one molal solution", i.e. a solution which contains one mole of the solute per kilogram of the solvent. The SI unit for molality is mol/kg.
terms.label: molal concentration of an entity

description: Molarity, or molar concentration, denotes the number of moles of a given substance per litre of solution. The unit of measure of molarity is mol/L, molar, or the capital letter M as an abbreviated form.
terms.label: molar concentration of an entity

description: Term to signify where a material or conceptual entity is represented or denoted by a symbol or by some other abbreviated form.
terms.label: denotement

description: Mathematical function commonly used in biological modeling,  which enable simplification of more complex expressions
terms.label: convenience function

description: Synonym: input signal step function
terms.label: periodic forcing function

description: The period is the duration of one cycle in a repeating event. [wikipedia]
terms.label: period

description: Synonym: temporal offset
terms.label: phase shift

description: The product of the Michaelis constants, to the power of their respective stoichiometric coefficients, for either substrates or products.
terms.label: powered product of Michaelis constant

description: The product of the substrate Michaelis constants, to the power of their respective stoichiometric coefficients.
terms.label: powered product of substrate Michaelis constants

description: The product of the product Michaelis constants, to the power of their respective stoichiometric coefficients.
terms.label: powered product of product Michaelis constants

description: The stoichiometric coefficient represents the degree to which a chemical species participates in a reaction. It corresponds to the number of molecules of a reactant that are consumed or produced with each occurrence of a reaction event.
terms.label: stoichiometric coefficient

description: The geometric mean turnover rate of an enzyme in either forward or backward direction for a reaction, measured per second.
terms.label: geometric mean rate constant

description: The geometric mean turnover rate of an enzyme in the forward direction for a reaction, measured per second.
terms.label: forward geometric mean rate constant

description: The geometric mean turnover rate of an enzyme in the reverse direction for a reaction, measured per second.
terms.label: reverse geometric mean rate constant

description: The minimal velocity observed under defined conditions, which may or may not include the presence of an effector. For example in an inhibitory system, this would be the residual velocity observed under full inhibition. In non-essential activation, this would be the velocity in the absence of any activator.
terms.label: basal rate constant

description: The ratio of the basal activity to the maximal velocity of a reaction. The values range between 0 and 1.
terms.label: relative basal rate constant

description: Function which ranges from 0 to 1, to describe the relative activation or inhibition of a reaction or process, actual or conceptual.
terms.label: relative activity function

description: Function which ranges from 0 to 1, to describe the relative activation of a reaction or process, actual or conceptual.
terms.label: relative activation function

description: Function which ranges from 0 to 1, to describe the relative inhibition of a reaction or process, actual or conceptual.
terms.label: relative inhibition function

description: Number of molecules which are generated by an enzyme.
terms.label: number of products

description: Synonym: diffusivity
terms.label: diffusion coefficient

description: Amplitude is the magnitude of change in the oscillating variable, with each oscillation, within an oscillating system.
terms.label: amplitude

description: A spatial region of an entity that confers a function
terms.label: functional domain

description: A specific domain of a spatio-temporal entity to which another spatio-temporal entity is able to bind, forming chemical bonds.
terms.label: binding site

description: A catalytic site is the region which confers specificity of a substrate for the binding entity, and where specific reactions take place in the conversion of the substrate to the product.
terms.label: catalytic site

description: A transmembrane domain is any three-dimensional protein structure which is thermodynamically stable in a membrane. This may be a single alpha helix, a stable complex of several transmembrane alpha helices, a transmembrane beta barrel, a beta-helix of gramicidin A, or any other structure.
terms.label: transmembrane domain

description: A parameter that has three discrete values which may be alternated between.
terms.label: ternary switch

description: Value which ranges from 0 to 1, to describe the relative activity of a process or reaction.
terms.label: relative activity

description: A phenomenon whereby an observed phenotype, qualitative or quantative,  is not explainable by the simple additive effects of the individual gene pertubations alone. Genetic interaction between perturbed genes is usually expected to generate a 'defective' phenotype. The level of defectiveness is often used to sub-classify this phenomenon.
terms.label: genetic interaction

description: Genetic suppression is said to have occurred when the phenotypic effect of an initial mutation in a gene is less severe, or entirely negated, by a subsequent mutation.
terms.label: genetic suppression

description: Genetic enhancement is said to have occurred when the phenotypic effect of an initial mutation in a gene is made increasingly severe by a subsequent mutation.
terms.label: genetic enhancement

description: Synthetic lethality is said to have occurred where gene mutations, each of which map to a separate locus, fail to complement in an offspring to correct a phenotype, as would be expected.
terms.label: synthetic lethality

description: The numerical quantification of an entity pool. This may be expressed as, for example, the number of molecules or the number of moles of identical entities of which an specific entity pool is comprised.
terms.label: number of entity pool constituents

description: The mass that comprises an entity pool.
terms.label: mass of an entity pool

description: Amount of enzyme present per unit of volume. The participant role 'enzymatic catalyst' is defined in SBO:0000460.
terms.label: concentration of enzyme

description: Amount, expressed as a mass, of an enzyme. The participant role 'enzymatic catalyst' is defined in SBO:0000460.
terms.label: mass of enzyme

description: Amount, expressed as a number, of a specific enzyme comprising an entity pool. This may be expressed, for example, as the number of molecules, or the number of moles. The participant role 'enzymatic catalyst' is defined in SBO:0000460.
terms.label: number of an enzyme

description: The amount, expressed as a number, of a specific reactant comprising an entity pool. This may be expressed, for example, as the number of molecules, or the number of moles. The participant role 'reactant' is defined in SBO:0000010.
terms.label: number of a reactant

description: The amount of a specific entity pool reactant present per unit of volume. The participant role 'reactant' is defined in SBO:0000010.
terms.label: concentration of reactant

description: The amount, expressed as a mass, of a specific reactant entity pool. The participant role 'reactant' is defined in SBO:0000010.
terms.label: mass of reactant

description: The amount, expressed as a number, of a specific product comprising an entity pool. This may be expressed, for example, as the number of molecules, or the number of moles. The participant role 'product' is defined in SBO:0000011.
terms.label: number of a product

description: The amount of a specific entity pool product present per unit of volume. The participant role 'product' is defined in SBO:0000011.
terms.label: concentration of product

description: The amount, expressed as a mass, of a specific product entity pool. The participant role 'product' is defined in SBO:0000011.
terms.label: mass of product

description: The amount, expressed as a number, of a specific substrate comprising an entity pool. This may be expressed, for example, as the number of molecules, or the number of moles. The participant role 'substrate' is defined in SBO:0000015.
terms.label: number of a substrate

description: The amount of a specific entity pool substrate present per unit of volume. The participant role 'substrate' is defined in SBO:0000015.
terms.label: concentration of substrate

description: The amount, expressed as a mass, of a specific substrate entity pool. The participant role 'substrate' is defined in SBO:0000015.
terms.label: mass of substrate

description: The amount, expressed as a number, of a specific modifier comprising an entity pool. This may be expressed, for example, as the number of molecules, or the number of moles. The participant role 'modifier' is defined in SBO:0000019.
terms.label: number of a modifier

description: The amount of a specific modifier entity pool present per unit of volume. The participant role 'modifier' is defined in SBO:0000019.
terms.label: concentration of modifier

description: The amount, expressed as a mass, of a specific modifier entity pool. The participant role 'modifier' is defined in SBO:0000019.
terms.label: mass of modifier

description: The amount, expressed as a number, of a specific inhibitor comprising an entity pool. This may be expressed, for example, as the number of molecules, or the number of moles. The participant role 'inhibitor' is defined in SBO:0000020.
terms.label: number of an inhibitor

description: The amount of a specific inhibitor entity pool present per unit of volume. The participant role 'inhibitor' is defined in SBO:0000020.
terms.label: concentration of inhibitor

description: The amount, expressed as a mass, of a specific inhibitor entity pool. The participant role 'inhibitor' is defined in SBO:0000020.
terms.label: mass of inhibitor

description: The amount, expressed as a number, of a specific activator comprising an entity pool. This may be expressed, for example, as the number of molecules, or the number of moles. The participant role 'activator' is defined in SBO:0000459.
terms.label: number of an activator

description: The amount of a specific activator entity pool present per unit of volume. The participant role 'activator' is defined in SBO:0000459.
terms.label: concentration of activator

description: The amount, expressed as a mass, of a specific activator entity pool. The participant role 'activator' is defined in SBO:0000459.
terms.label: mass of activator

description: The process by which two or more proteins interact non-covalently to form a protein complex (SBO:0000297).
terms.label: protein complex formation
modular rate law

description: The common modular rate law is a generalised form of reversible Michaelis Menten kinetics, using a denominator where each binding state of the enzyme is represented. It is assumed that substrates and products bind independently and randomly, and that substrates and products cannot be bound at the same time.
terms.label: common modular rate law

description: The direct binding modular rate law makes the assumption that both substrates and products bind simultaneously and in a single step, hence the total binding states possible enumerate to 3; nothing bound, substrates bound, and products bound. Substrates and products cannot be bound at the same time.
terms.label: direct binding modular rate law

description: The simultaneous binding modular rate law makes the assumption that substrates and products can be bound simultaneously, and in any combination.
terms.label: simultaneous binding modular rate law

description: For the power-law rate law, the denominator is set to be a constant, and the rate law does not saturate.
terms.label: power-law modular rate law

description:
Modular rate law where the D term is given by the square root of the product of
terms (c/KM)^m where c, KM, and m denote the concentrations, Michaelis constants, and molecularities, respectively, and the product is taken over all reactants and products involved in the reaction.
terms.label: force-dependent modular rate law

description:
An essential activator that affects the apparent value of the specificity
constant. Mechanistically, the activator would need to be bound before
reactant and product binding can take place.
terms.label: specific activator

description:
An essential activator that affects the apparent value of the catalytic
constant.
terms.label: catalytic activator

description:
An essential activator that affects the apparent value of the Michaelis
constant(s).
terms.label: binding activator

description:
Substance that, when bound, decreases enzymatic activity to a lower,
nonzero value, without itself being consumed or transformed by the
reaction, and without sterically hindering the interaction between
reactants. The enzyme-inhibitor complex does retain some basal level of activity.
terms.label: partial inhibitor

description:
Substance that, when bound, completely negates enzymatic activity, without
itself being consumed or transformed by the reaction, and without
sterically hindering the interaction between reactants. The inhibitor
binds to all enzyme species independently and with the same affinity,
completely inhibiting any enzymatic activity.
terms.label: complete inhibitor

description: Synonym: membrane permeability
terms.label: ionic permeability

description: A quantitative parameter that represents a probability value, assigned to a specific event.
terms.label: probabilistic parameter

description: A ratio that represents the quantity of a defined constituent entity over the total number of all constituent entities present.
terms.label: fraction of an entity pool

description: The number of moles of a constituent entity, divided by the total number of all constituent entities present in a system.
terms.label: mole fraction

description: Synonym: R0
terms.label: basic reproductive ratio

description: A nonspecific coalescence of misfolded proteins which may or may not form a precipitate, depending upon particle size.
terms.label: protein aggregate

description: Supplementary information relating to a primary item of data, traditionally termed 'data about data'. It can describe, for example, the location or type of the data, or its relationship to other data.
terms.label: metadata representation

description: A value, numerical or symbolic, that defines certain characteristics of systems or system functions, or is necessary in their derivation.
terms.label: systems description parameter

description: A non-numerical value that defines certain characteristics of systems or system functions.
terms.label: qualitative systems description parameter

description: Equationally defined algebraic framework usually interpreted as a two-valued logic using the basic Boolean operations (conjunction, disjunction and negation), together with the constants '0' and '1' denoting false and true values, respectively.
terms.label: boolean logical framework

description: Extension of the boolean logical framework which associates a defined number of possible integer values (states) with the variables.
terms.label: multi-valued logical framework

description: Extension of the Boolean logical framework which allows intermediate or undetermined values for the logical variables.
terms.label: fuzzy logical framework

description: Supplementary information that does not modify the semantics of the presented information.
terms.label: annotation

description: The use of an abbreviated name, taken from a controlled vocabulary of terms, which is used to represent some information about the entity to which it is attached.
terms.label: controlled short label

description: Additional information that supplements existing data, usually in a document, by providing a link to more detailed information, which is held externally, or elsewhere.
terms.label: reference annotation

description: An annotation which directs one to information contained within a published body of knowledge, usually a book or scientific journal.
terms.label: bibliographical reference

description: Synonym: db xref
terms.label: database cross reference

description: Annotation which complies with the full set of defined rules in its construction.
terms.label: controlled annotation

description: Annotation which does not comply with, or is not restricted by, any rules in its construction. Examples would include free text annotations.
terms.label: uncontrolled annotation

description: Annotation that directly incorporates information into the body of a document.
terms.label: embedded annotation

description: A measure of enzyme activity under standard conditions, at a specific substrate concentration (usually saturation), expressed as the amount of product formed per unit time, per amount of enzyme. This is often expressed as micromol per min per mg, rather than the less practical official unit, Katal (1 mol per second).
terms.label: specific activity

description: A measure of the amount of active enzyme present, expressed under specified conditions. This is often expressed as micromol per min (also known as enzyme unit, U), rather than the less practical official SI unit, Katal (1 mol per second). Enzyme activity normally refers to the natural substrate for the enzyme, but can also be given for standardised substrates such as gelatin, where it is then referred to as GDU (Gelatin Digesting Units).
terms.label: enzyme activity

description: Reaction scheme in which the reaction velocity is direct proportional to the activity or concentration of a single molecular species. The reaction scheme does not include any reverse process that creates the reactants from the products. The change of a product quantity is proportional to the quantity of the stimulator. It is to be used in a reaction modelled using a continuous framework.
terms.label: mass action rate law for first order irreversible reactions, single essential stimulator, continuous scheme

parents.label: mass action rate law for irreversible reactions, continuous scheme

description: Reaction scheme in which the reaction velocity is direct proportional to the activity or quantity of a single molecular species. The reaction scheme does not include any reverse process that creates the reactants from the products. The change of a product quantity is proportional to the quantity of the stimulator. It is to be used in a reaction modelled using a discrete framework.
terms.label: mass action rate law for first order irreversible reactions, single essential stimulator, discrete scheme

parents.label: mass action rate law for irreversible reactions, discrete scheme

description: Reaction scheme where the products are created from a reactant and the change of a product quantity is proportional to the product of the reactant and the stimulator activities. The reaction scheme does not include any reverse process that creates the reactant from the products. The change of a product quantity is proportional to the quantity of the reactant and the stimulator.
terms.label: mass action like rate law for second order irreversible reactions, one reactant, one essential stimulator

parents.label: mass action rate law for second order irreversible reactions

description: Reaction scheme where the products are created from a reactant and the change of a product quantity is proportional to the product of the reactant and the stimulator activities. The reaction scheme does not include any reverse process that creates the reactant from the products. The change of a product quantity is proportional to the quantity of the reactant and the stimulator. It is to be used in a reaction modelled using a continuous framework.
terms.label: mass action like rate law for second order irreversible reactions, one reactant, one essential stimulator, continuous scheme

parents.label: mass action like rate law for second order irreversible reactions, one reactant, one essential stimulator

description: Reaction scheme where the products are created from a reactant and the change of a product quantity is proportional to the product of the reactant and the stimulator quantities. The reaction scheme does not include any reverse process that creates the reactant from the products. The change of a product quantity is proportional to the quantity of the reactant and the stimulator. It is to be used in a reaction modelled using a discrete framework.
terms.label: mass action like rate law for second order irreversible reactions, one reactant, one essential stimulator, discrete scheme

parents.label: mass action like rate law for second order irreversible reactions, one reactant, one essential stimulator

description: A physical constant that is required in the calculation of a system parameter.
terms.label: systems description constant

description: The permeability of an ion through a channel or membrane expressed in relation to the reference ion, which is given the value 1. For example, if a membrane is most permeable to K+, then that is assigned the reference permeability value of 1, and the value for Na+ may be 0.05.
terms.label: relative permeability

description: Synonym: molar gas constant
terms.label: universal gas constant

description: Named after Michael Faraday, it is the magnitude of electric charge per mole of electrons. It has the value 96,485.3365 C/mol (Coulombs per Mole), and the symbol F.
terms.label: Faraday constant

description: Synonym: Goldman-Hodgkin-Katz voltage equation
terms.label: Goldman equation

description: Synonym: reversal potential
terms.label: Nernst potential

description:
Parameters used in the study of thermodynamics, a physical science that
pertains to the relationship between heat and other forms of energy such
as 'work done' in material bodies.
terms.label: thermodynamic parameter

description:
A thermodynamic potential whose natural variables are entropy (S) and
pressure (p). The enthalpy of a system, measured in Joules (J), is defined
as H = U + pV (where H is enthalpy, U is the internal energy, p is the
pressure at the system boundary, and V is the system volume).
symbol: H
terms.label: enthalpy

description:
Change in enthalpy observed in the constituents of a thermodynamic system
when undergoing a transformation or chemical reaction. This is the
preferred way of expressing the energy changes to a system at constant
pressure, since enthalpy itself cannot be directly measured. The enthalpy
change is positive in endothermic reactions, negative in exothermic
reactions, and is defined as the difference between the final and initial enthalpy of the system under study: ΔH = Hf - Hi. The standard unit of measure is J. Symbol: ΔH
terms.label: enthalpy change

description:
The enthalpy change observed in a constituent of a thermodynamic system
when one mole of a compound, in its standard state, is formed from its
elementary antecedents, in their standard state(s), under standard
conditions (1 bar). The standard unit of measure is kJ/mol.
Symbol: DeltaHf0, DeltafH0
terms.label: standard enthalpy of formation

description:
The enthalpy change observed in a constituent of a thermodynamic system
when one mole of substance reacts completely, under standard conditions (1
bar). The standard unit of measure is kJ/mol.
Symbol: DeltaHr0, DeltarH0
terms.label: standard enthalpy of reaction

description:
A thermodynamic property which acts as a measure of the state of disorder
of a system. Its natural variables are the internal energy (U) and the
volume (V). It is defined by dS = (1/T)dU + (p/T)dV. The second law of
thermodynamics states that in an isolated system, natural processes tend
to increase in disorder or entropy. The standard unit of measure is Joules
per Kelvin (J/K).
symbol: S
terms.label: entropy

description:
The increase or decrease of the entropy of a system. For values greater
than zero, there is an implied increase in the disorder of a system, for
example during a reaction, and decreased disorder where the values are
less than zero. The entropy change of a process is defined as the initial
system entropy value minus the final entropy value: DeltaS = Sf - Si. The
standard unit of measure is J/K.
symbol: DeltaS
terms.label: entropy change

description:
The entropy change observed in a thermodynamic system when one mole of
substance reacts completely, under standard conditions (1 bar).  The
standard unit of measure is kJ/(mol K). This can be calculated using the
entropies for products and reactants: DeltaS(reaction)=sum DeltaS (products) - sum DeltaS reactants. The standard unit of measure is kJ/(mol K).
symbol: DeltaSro
terms.label: standard entropy of reaction

description:
The change in entropy associated with the formation of one mole of a
substance from its elements in their standard states under standard
conditions (1 bar). The standard unit of measure is kJ/(mol K).
symbol: DeltaSfo
terms.label: standard entropy of formation

description: Synonym: Gibbs function
terms.label: Gibbs free energy

description:
The increase or decrease of the Gibbs free energy of a system. During a
reaction, this is equal to the change in enthalpy of the system minus the
change in the product of the temperature times the entropy of the system: ΔG = ΔH - T ΔS. A negative value indicates that the reaction will be favoured and will
release energy. The magnitude of the value indicates how far the reaction
is from equilibrium, where there will be no free energy change. The
standard unit of measure is kJ/mol. Symbol: ΔG.
terms.label: Gibbs free energy change

description: The change in Gibbs free energy associated with the formation of 1 mole of substance from elements in their standard states under standard conditions (1 bar). For aqueous solutions, each solute must be present in 1M concentration. The standard unit of measure is kJ/mol. Symbol: ΔGf°.
terms.label: standard Gibbs free energy of formation

description:
The Gibbs free energy change observed in a thermodynamic system when one
mole of substance reacts completely, under standard conditions (1 bar). For aqueous solutions, each solute must be present in 1M concentration. The standard unit of measure is kJ/mol. Symbol: ΔG°.
terms.label: standard Gibbs free energy of reaction

description: A duration of time after which a phase shift occurs.
terms.label: temporal offset

description: The total length of time over which a model is simulated, where the time scale is indicated within the model simulation.
terms.label: simulation duration

description: A conceptualisation of time which is intrinsic to a mathematical model, and which can be used to describe other variables or parameters of the model.
terms.label: model time

description: A transport reaction which results in the entry of the transported entity, into the cell.
terms.label: transcellular membrane influx reaction

description: A transport reaction which results in the removal of the transported entity from the cell.
terms.label: transcellular membrane efflux reaction

description: A composite biochemical process through which a gene sequence is fully converted into mature gene products. These gene products may include RNA species as well as proteins, and the process encompasses all intermediate steps required to generate the active form of the gene product.
terms.label: genetic production

description: A stretch of DNA upstream of a transcription start site, to which a promoter and other transcription factors may bind to initiate or regulate expression.
terms.label: promoter

description: A process that can modify the state of petri net 'places'[SBO:0000593].
terms.label: petri net transition

description: A discrete value attributed to an entity pool.
terms.label: discrete amount of an entity pool

description: A defined entity pool state which can be modified by a petri net transition [SBO:0000591].
terms.label: petri net place

parents.label: discrete amount of an entity pool

description: A participant whose presence does not alter the velocity of a process or event.
terms.label: neutral participant

description:
A modifier that can exhibit either inhibitory or stimulatory effects on a
process depending on the context in which it occurs. For example, the observed effect may be dependent upon the concentration of the modifier.
terms.label: dual-activity modifier

description: A modifier whose activity is not known or has not been specified.
terms.label: modifier of unknown activity

description: A silencer is a modifier which acts in a manner that completely prevents an event or process from occurring. For example, a silencer in gene expression is usually a transcription factor that binds a DNA sequence in such a way as to completely prevent the binding of RNA polymerase, and thus fully suppresses transcription.
terms.label: silencer

description: A region of DNA to which various transcription factors and RNA polymerase must bind in order to initiate transcription for a gene.
terms.label: promoter

description: A denotement that specifies a point of contact between variables or submodels in a hierarchical model.
terms.label: port

description: A connection point to an element in a model that indicates that the element's mathematical interpretation is defined outside the model.
terms.label: input port

description: A connection point to an element in a model that indicates that the element's mathematical interpretation is defined within the model.
terms.label: output port

description: A parameter that takes only logical values.
terms.label: logical parameter

description: A substance that is produced in a chemical reaction but is not itself the primary product or focus of that reaction. Examples include, but are not limited to, currency compounds such as ATP, NADPH and protons.
terms.label: side product

description: A substance that is consumed in a chemical reaction but is not itself the primary substrate or focus of that reaction. Examples include, but are not limited to, currency compounds such as ATP, NADPH and protons.
terms.label: side substrate

description: A receptor where binding occurs through strong intermolecular forces such as Van der Waals, hydrogen bonds or ionic bonds.
terms.label: high affinity receptor

description: A receptor where binding occurs through weak intermolecular forces.
terms.label: low affinity receptor

description: A macromolecular complex composed of two monomeric units, which may or may not be identical. Monomers are usually non-covalently bound.
terms.label: dimer

description: A macromolecular complex composed of precisely two identical monomeric units, which are usually non-covalently bound.
terms.label: homodimer

description: A macromolecular complex composed of precisely two non-identical monomeric units, which are usually non-covalently bound.
terms.label: heterodimer

description: A measure of the rate of growth of an organism, usually in culture. This can be expressed as increase in cell number or, more usually as an increase in dry weight of cells (grams), measured over a unit time period. Usually expressed as hour -1.
terms.label: growth rate

description: Under nutrient limited conditions, it may be assumed that enzymes are operating below their maximal capacity (Kcat). Keff represents the lumped turnover rate of a reaction, expressed in units per time.
terms.label: effective catalytic rate

description: The velocity at which a reaction occurs. This may be calculated through the accumulation of a product or consumption of a reactant, and expressed using entity concentrations or amounts per time interval. The rate of reaction may be influenced by temperature, pressure and other factors. Rate of reaction is often referred to as reaction rate or metabolic flux.
terms.label: rate of reaction

description: Parameters that pertain to chemical reactions.
terms.label: reaction parameter

description: Rate of reaction expressed as a change in concentration over time.
terms.label: rate of reaction (concentration)

description: Rate of reaction expressed as a change in enumerated quantity over time.
terms.label: rate of reaction (amount)

description: The extent of a reaction is a measure of how far a reaction has proceeded towards equilibrium. It is denoted by the Greek letter Î¾ and is expressed in moles.
terms.label: extent of reaction

description: The Gibbs free energy change observed in a thermodynamic system when a substance undergoes a reaction under non standard conditions. The unit of measure is kJ/mol. Symbol: ΔG.
terms.label: Gibbs free energy of reaction

description: Synonym: thermodynamic driving force
terms.label: reaction affinity

description: A Gibbs free energy that is calculated from the standard Gibbs value (at 298K), and extrapolated to a desired pH and ionic strength, and may be determined at a different temperature. Symbol: ΔG´.
terms.label: transformed Gibbs free energy change

description: A Gibbs free energy of reaction that is calculated from the standard Gibbs value (at 298K), and extrapolated to a desired pH and ionic strength, and may be determined at a different temperature. Symbol ΔG´.
terms.label: transformed standard Gibbs free energy of reaction

description: A Gibbs free energy of formation that is calculated from the standard Gibbs value (at 298K), and extrapolated to a desired pH and ionic strength, and may be determined at a different temperature. Symbol ΔGf´.
terms.label: transformed standard Gibbs free energy of formation

description: The Gibbs free energy change observed in a thermodynamic system when a substance undergoes a reaction under non standard conditions, which is extrapolated to a desired pH and ionic strength, and may be determined at a different temperature. Symbol: ΔG´.
terms.label: transformed Gibbs free energy of reaction

description: A combined (weighted) measure of the concentration of all electrolytes present in a solution. It is calculated as a half of the sum over all the ions in the solution multiplied by the square of individual ionic valencies. Monovalent electrolytes have a concentration equal to their ionic strength while multivalent electrolytes have greater ionic strength, directly proportional to ionic valency. Symbol: I
terms.label: ionic strength

description: Modelling approach, typically used for metabolic models, where the flow of metabolites (flux) through a network can be calculated. This approach will generally produce a set of solutions (solution space), which may be reduced using objective functions and constraints on individual fluxes.
terms.label: flux balance framework

description: A parameter that limits the upper or lower value that a flux may assume. This parameter may be determined experimentally, or may be the result of theoretical investigation.
terms.label: flux bound

description: A value used for flux bound in cases where a precise value, supported experimentally or theoretically, is not available.
terms.label: default flux bound

description: A modeling process to provide matter influx or efflux to a model, for example to replenish a metabolic network with raw materials (eg carbon / energy sources). Such reactions are conceptual, created solely for modeling purposes, and do not have a physical correspondence. Exchange reactions, often represented as 'R_EX_', can operate in the negative (uptake) direction or positive (secretion) direction. By convention, a negative flux through an exchange reaction represents uptake of the corresponding metabolite, and a positive flux represent discharge.
terms.label: exchange reaction

description: A modeling process analogous to exchange reaction, but which operates upon "internal" metabolites. Metabolites that are consumed by these reactions are assumed to be used in intra-cellular processes that are not part of the model. Demand reactions, often represented 'R_DM_', can also deliver metabolites (from intra-cellular processes that are not considered in the model).
terms.label: demand reaction

description: Biomass production, often represented 'R_BIOMASS_', is usually the optimization target reaction of constraint-based models, and can consume multiple reactants to produce multiple products. It is also assumed that parts of the reactants are also consumed in unrepresented processes and hence products do not have to reflect all the atom composition of the reactants. Formulation of a biomass production process entails definition of the macromolecular content (eg. cellular protein fraction), metabolic constitution of each fraction (eg. amino acids), and subsequently the atomic composition (eg. nitrogen atoms). More complex biomass functions can additionally incorporate details of essential vitamins and cofactors required for growth.
terms.label: biomass production

description: Synonym: maintenance energy
terms.label: ATP maintenance

description: A conceptual process used for modeling purposes, often created solely to complete model structure, with respect to providing inflow or outflow of matter or material. Unlike other reactions, pseudoreactions are not usually subjected to mass balance considerations.
terms.label: pseudoreaction

description: Synonym: source/sink
terms.label: sink reaction

description: Term used to indicate the grouping of model components, largely reactions, by some criterion, often processual. This can be used to indicate, for example, the subsystem of a model that is concerned with 'transport'. A designated subsystem includes reactions annotated with the term, as well as reactions participants such as enzymes, modifiers and genes encoding these subsystem components.
terms.label: subsystem

description: Fragment or region of a DNA macromolecule.
terms.label: DNA segment

description: Fragment or region of an RNA macromolecule.
terms.label: RNA segment

description: Synonym: positive allosteric modulation
terms.label: allosteric activator

description: Describes an activator (ligand) which binds to the enzyme, which does not result in a conformational change, but which enhances the enzyme's activity.
terms.label: non-allosteric activator

description: An inhibitor which binds irreversibly with the enzyme such that it cannot be removed, and abolishes enzymatic function.
terms.label: irreversible inhibitor

description: An inhibitor whose binding to an enzyme results in a conformational change, resulting in a loss of enzymatic activity. This activity can be restored upon removal of the inhibitor.
terms.label: allosteric inhibitor

description: Synonym: anti-competitive inhibitor
terms.label: uncompetitive inhibitor

description: An enumeration of the concentration of magnesium (Mg) in solution (pMg = -log10[Mg2+]).
terms.label: pMg

description: Conceptual or material entity that is the object of an inhibition process, and is acted upon by an inhibitor.
terms.label: inhibited

description: Conceptual or material entity that is the object of a stimulation process, and is acted upon by a stimulator.
terms.label: stimulated

description: Conceptual or material entity that is the object of a modification process, and is acted upon by a modifier.
terms.label: modified

description: An entity that acts as the starting material for genetic production (http://identifiers.org/biomodels.sbo/SBO:0000589).
terms.label: template

description: Reaction scheme where the products are created from the reactants and the change of a product quantity is proportional to the product of reactant activities. The reaction scheme includes a reverse process that creates the reactants from the products. It is to be used in a reaction modelled using a continuous framework.
terms.label: mass action rate law for reversible reactions, continuous schema

parents.label: mass action rate law for reversible reactions

description: Synonym: molecular weight
terms.label: molecular mass

description: Synonym: protein molecular weight
terms.label: protein molecular mass

description: A composite representation of material entities required for organismal growth. It includes macromolecular content (eg. cellular protein fraction), metabolic constitution of each fraction (eg. amino acids), and atomic composition (eg. nitrogen atoms).
terms.label: biomass

description: A sequential series of actions, motions, or occurrences, such as chemical reactions, where a reversal of states that bring the system back to its original state in a characteristic manner occurs.
terms.label: reversible process

description: A sequential series of actions, motions, or occurrences, such as chemical reactions, where a reversal of states that bring the system back to its original state in a characteristic manner does not occur.
terms.label: irreversible process

description: A chemical reaction in which one or more monomer molecules combine to form a larger polymer molecule with repeated structural units.
terms.label: polymerization

description: A chemical reaction in which a large polymer breaks into its constituent monomers (or mixture of monomers).
terms.label: depolymerization

description: A biochemical process involving the simultaneous transport of two or more substances across a membrane via a protein or protein complex.
terms.label: co-transport reaction

description: The movement of an entity/entities across a biological membrane mediated by a transporter protein.
terms.label: transport reaction

description: A conformational change in a protein resulting in its activation.
terms.label: activation

description: Protein assisted movement of molecules across a membrane from a region of low concentration to high concentration involving the consumption of cellular energy (ATP molecules).
terms.label: active transport

description: Movement of molecules without the need for external energy, and usually from a region of high concentration to low concentration.
terms.label: passive transport

description: A membrane protein mediated transport of two ore more molecules in the same relative direction across a membrane.
terms.label: symporter-mediated transport

description: A membrane protein mediated transport of two or more molecules in opposite directions across a membrane.
terms.label: antiporter-mediated transport

description: Total amount that can be contained or produced by a specific entity. This can refer to diverse items, such as the carrying capacity of a membrane with respect to proteins, the capacity of high-energy phosphate bonds, or the maximal count of bacteria in the gut, etc.
terms.label: capacity

description: Occopancy is a quantitative systemic property that indicates which number of available places is occupied. This can refer to diverse things, such as the number of occupied high-energy phosphate bonds in ATP, the number of bacteria in the gut, or the number of electrons loaded onto redox carriers, etc.
terms.label: occupancy

description: Fractional occupancy is a quantitative dynamic property of a system that can be calculated as the fraction of occupancy over capacity.
terms.label: fractional occupancy

description: an entity which physical constituents are partially or totally contained in a defined compartment.
terms.label: contained entity

description: a conformation changes to a protein leading to its inactivation
terms.label: inactivation

description: describes the number of amino acids,nucleic acid in a protein/DNA/RNA chain
terms.label: chain length

description: length of amino acid sequence in a protein
terms.label: protein chain length

description: output generated as biomass or product from a/set of chemical reaction/s.
terms.label: yield

description: generation of biomass for an substrate through a defined reaction/s.
terms.label: biomass yield on substrate

description: generation of product from substrate in a defined chemical reaction.
terms.label: product yield on substrate

description: agent driving non-enzymatic reaction. Non-enzymatic reactions resemble catalytic mechanisms as found in all major enzyme classes and occur spontaneously, small molecule (e.g. metal-) catalyzed or light-induced.
terms.label: non-enzymatic catalyst

description: Reaction with no catalyst (no enzyme in particular) is needed to proceed.
terms.label: spontaneous reaction

description: it represent the catalytic rate driving the reaction in forward direction.
terms.label: forward effective catalytic rate

description: it represent the catalytic rate driving the reaction in backward direction.
terms.label: reverse effective catalytic rate

description: Modeling approach where the quantities of participants are considered deterministic continuous variables, and represented by real values. The associated simulation methods make use of ordinary differential equations.
terms.label: deterministic non-spatial continuous framework

description: Modeling approach where the quantities of participants are considered stochastic continuous variables, and represented by real values. The associated simulation methods make use of stochastic differential equations. The models do take into account the distribution of the entities.
terms.label: stochastic non-spatial continuous framework

description: Modeling approach which tracks the sizes of populations of participants in each spatial localization. For biochemical simulations, such populations could represent types of molecular species.
terms.label: population-based discrete spatial simulation

description: Modeling approach which tracks the state of individual particles in each spatial localization. For biochemical simulations, such particles could represent individual molecules.
terms.label: particle-based discrete spatial simulation

description: Modeling approach which tracks the sizes of populations of participants with minimal or no spatial resolution. For biochemical simulations, such populations could represent types of molecular species.
terms.label: population-based discrete non-spatial simulation

description: Modeling approach which tracks the state of individual particles with miimal or no spatial resolution. For biochemical simulations, such particles could represent individual molecules.
terms.label: particle-based discrete non-spatial simulation

description: Modeling approach which combines multiple canonical modeling frameworks. For example, a hybrid model could consider both continuous (represented by real values) and discrete (represented by integers) participants. Hybrid models are executed with hybrid simulation algorithms. For example, a hybrid continuous-discrete model may be simulation using a combination of stochastic simulation and ordinary differential equations.
terms.label: hybrid framework

description: Modeling approach which combines multiple canonical spatial modeling frameworks. For example, a hybrid model could consider both continuous (represented by real values) and discrete (represented by integers) participants. Hybrid models are executed with hybrid simulation algorithms. For example, a hybrid continuous-discrete model may be simulation using a combination of stochastic simulation and partial differential equations.
terms.label: hybrid spatial framework

description: Modeling approach which combines multiple canonical non-spatial modeling frameworks. For example, a hybrid model could consider both continuous (represented by real values) and discrete (represented by integers) participants. Hybrid models are executed with hybrid simulation algorithms.
